, written off. This aircraft is now in the Ukraine Government Museum of Aviation.\n|align=center|<ref>{{ASN accident|title= CCCP-85020|id= 19769999-3|access-date= 21 December 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=center|{{dts|format=dmy|1977|12|2}}\n|align=center|LZ-BTN\n|align=center|Tu-154A\n| {{Flagicon|Libya|1977}} near [[Benghazi]]\n|align=center|{{nts|59|}}/165\n| [[1977 Benghazi Libyan Arab Airlines Tu-154 crash|Crashed]] due to fuel exhaustion while searching for an alternate airport after diverting due to fog. The aircraft was leased from Balkan Bulgarian Airlines.\n|align=center|<ref>{{ASN accident|title= LZ-BTN|id= 19771202-0|access-date= 21 December 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=center|{{dts|format=dmy|1978|3|23}}\n|align=center|LZ-BTB\n|align=center|Tu-154B\n| {{Flagicon|Syria}} near [[Damascus]]\n|align=center|{{nts|4}}/4\n| Crashed into high ground on final approach.\n|align=center|<ref>{{ASN accident|title= LZ-BTB|id= 19780323-1|access-date= 21 December 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=center|{{dts|format=dmy|1978|5|19}}\n|align=center|CCCP-85169\n|align=center|Tu-154B\n| {{Flagicon|USSR}} near [[Maksatikha]]\n|align=center|{{nts|4}}/134\n| Aeroflot Flight 6709 crashed in a field after all three engines failed after the flight engineer accidentally shut off the automatic transferring of fuel of the sump tank.\n|align=center|<ref>{{ASN accident|title= CCCP-85169|id= 19780519-2|access-date= 21 December 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=center|{{dts|format=dmy|1979|6|30}}\n|align=center|P-551\n|align=center|Tu-154B\n| {{Flagicon|Hungary}} [[Budapest Ferenc Liszt International Airport|Ferihegy International Airport]]\n|align=center|{{nts|0}}\n| A [[Air Koryo|Choson Minhang]] charter flight stalled while landing due to pilot error. The right landing gear collapsed and the right wing hit the ground, sustaining damage to the wing structure. The aircraft was subsequently repaired and returned to service.\n|align=center|<ref>{{ASN accident|title= P-885|id= 19790630-1|access-date= 26 February 2