medical emergency due to a seriously ill passenger on board. The aircraft was leased from Kolavia.\n|align=center|<ref>{{ASN accident|title= RA-85787|id= 20100124-0|access-date= 28 December 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=center|{{dts|format=dmy|2010|4|10}}\n|align=center|''101''\n|align=center|Tu-154M\n| {{Flagicon|RUS}} near [[Smolensk]]\n|align=center|{{nts|96}}/96\n| [[Smolensk air disaster|Crashed]] on final approach in thick fog on an airfield without ILS. Polish President [[Lech Kaczy\u0144ski]] and other high-ranking officials were on board and died in the crash.\n|align=center|<ref>{{ASN accident|title= 101|id= 20100410-0|access-date= 28 December 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=center|{{dts|format=dmy|2010|09|7}}\n|align=center|RA-85684\n|align=center|Tu-154M\n| {{Flagicon|RUS}} [[Izhma Airport]]\n|align=center|{{nts|0}}/81\n| [[Alrosa Flight 514]] made an emergency landing at a remote disused airfield after a total electrical failure in cruise, overran the runway and was damaged, but no-one was injured. In 2011, the aircraft was repaired, flown out and returned to service.\n|align=center|<ref>[http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2010/09/07/347069/alrosa-tu-154-overruns-after-emergency-landing-in-russia.html Alrosa Tu-154 overruns after emergency landing in Russia ] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100911023651/http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2010/09/07/347069/alrosa-tu-154-overruns-after-emergency-landing-in-russia.html |date=11 September 2010 }}, [[FlightGlobal]], 7 September 2010</ref><ref>[http://rt.com/news/taiga-landing-tu-154/ Tu-154 back in the air six months after miracle landing in taiga] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121123093821/http://rt.com/news/taiga-landing-tu-154/ |date=23 November 2012 }}, [[RT (TV network)]], 24 March 2011</ref>\n|-\n|align=center|{{dts|format=dmy|2010|12|4}}\n|align=center|RA-85744\n|align=center|Tu-154M\n| {{Flagicon|RUS}} [[Domodedovo Airport]]\n|align=center|{{nts|2}}/170\n| [[Dagestan Airlines Flight 372]] made an emergency landing after two engines failed shortly after takeoff; full of fuel. Overran the runway and broke up into three. The accident investigation revealed that a crew member had mistakenly switched off a fuel transfer pump thereby causing fuel-starvation and subsequent engine flameout.\n|align=center|<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-11918769 BBC News \u2013 Two dead as engine failure airliner lands in Moscow] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170530071202/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-11918769 |date=30 May 2017 }}. Bbc.co.uk (4 December 2010). Retrieved on 10 December 2010.</ref>\n|-\n|align=center|{{dts|format=dmy|2011|01|1}}\n|align=center|RA-85588\n|align=center|Tu-154B-2\n| {{Flagicon|RUS}} [[Surgut International Airport]]\n|align=center|{{nts|3}}/124\n| [[Kolavia Flight 348]] caught fire while taxiing for takeoff.\n|align=center|<ref>[http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2011/01/01/world/main7202994.shtml?tag=stack Russian Passenger Jet Explodes; 3 Dead]. Cbsnews.com (1 January 2011).</ref>\n|-\n|align=center|{{dts|format=dmy|2016|12|25}}\n|align=center|RA-85572\n|align=center|Tu-154B-2\n| {{Flagicon|RUS}} [[Black Sea]], just off [[Sochi]]\n|align=center|{{nts|92}}/92\n| [[2016 Russian Defence Ministry Tupolev Tu-154 crash|Russian Defence Ministry flight]] crashed en route to [[Khmeimim]], Syria, killing all 92 people (84 passengers and 8 crew members) on board, including 64 members of the [[Alexandrov Ensemble]], an official army choir of the [[Armed Forces of the Russian Federation|Russian Armed Forces]]\n|align=center|<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.presstv.com/Detail/2016/12/25/503340/Russia-military-plane-Tu154- | title = PressTV-92 presumed dead in Russia military plane crash|access-date=25 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161225054646/http://presstv.com/Detail/2016/12/25/503340/Russia-military-plane-Tu154-|archive-date=25 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web 